resources.string:
        &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;What do I need?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br/&gt;
NFC-enabled Android phone&lt;br/&gt;
Some NFC-Tags&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;How do I get started?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br/&gt;
1. Go to &lt;strong&gt;Manage players&lt;/strong&gt; and add one or more players&lt;br/&gt;
2. Go to &lt;strong&gt;Manage cards (NFC-Tags) &lt;/strong&gt;and scan some tags.&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Information: &lt;/strong&gt;It will automatically choose the right pair size. So if you have ex. &lt;strong&gt;10 cards&lt;/strong&gt;, you will play with &lt;strong&gt;double pairs&lt;/strong&gt;. But if you have ex. &lt;strong&gt;9 cards&lt;/strong&gt;, you will play with &lt;strong&gt;triple pairs&lt;/strong&gt;. If both would be possible, you will get asked at the beginning of the game.&lt;br/&gt;
3. Click PLAY!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Who made this awesome game?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br/&gt;
The game was made by &lt;a href="http://jolau.ch" target="_blank"&gt;Jonas Lauener&lt;/a&gt; under the guidance of &lt;a href="http://www.gruntz.ch/" target="_blank"&gt;Dominik Gruntz&lt;/a&gt; at the &lt;a href="http://www.fhnw.ch/technik" target="_blank"&gt;FHNW&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
